she was doing

00:53:23.790 --> 00:53:25.830
that in her role as editor.

00:53:25.830 --> 00:53:27.850
And it wasn't much
of a critical --

00:53:27.850 --> 00:53:29.230
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: But that
is a kind of criticism though.

00:53:29.230 --> 00:53:30.530
I mean, you're trying to --

00:53:30.530 --> 00:53:31.830
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: It is.

00:53:31.830 --> 00:53:33.130
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: --
bail us out of the question,

00:53:33.130 --> 00:53:34.430
but we're going to
bail us back in.

00:53:34.430 --> 00:53:35.730
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: Yeah.

00:53:35.730 --> 00:53:37.030
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder:
That's is a kind of crazy.

00:53:37.030 --> 00:53:38.630
Anything is a kind of criticism
and -- but just to be fair,

00:53:38.630 --> 00:53:43.680
the note of apology was actually
written by both Stephanie Bird

00:53:43.680 --> 00:53:44.980
and [inaudible] who
are both the editors

00:53:44.980 --> 00:53:46.480
at the <i>Nation Magazine </i>.

00:53:46.480 --> 00:53:48.300
And the poet's name
is Anders Carlson.

00:53:48.300 --> 00:53:52.550
We -- and he wrote a kind of
bad poem basically about --

00:53:52.550 --> 00:53:54.600
from surfing the point of
view of a homeless person.

00:53:54.600 --> 00:53:56.400
And the real problem with
the poem is it was kind

00:53:56.400 --> 00:53:57.700
of a bad poem, actually.

00:53:57.700 --> 00:54:00.180
It wasn't -- it was
sort of a dumb poem.

00:54:00.180 --> 00:54:04.030
I mean the motivation
might also be problematic.

00:54:04.030 --> 00:54:05.550
I can't really speak to that,

00:54:05.550 --> 00:54:09.070
but I suppose I could imagine
some kind of platonic world,

00:54:09.070 --> 00:54:11.140
somebody writing a good poem
from that point of view.

00:54:11.140 --> 00:54:15.220
But it was sort of a stupid poem
that was not very well thought

00:54:15.220 --> 00:54:17.110
through in my opinion,
having read the poem.

00:54:17.110 --> 00:54:19.620
And it was just like -- I
think that was a lot of --

00:54:19.620 --> 00:54:20.920
&gt;&gt; Srikanth Reddy: Sure.

00:54:20.920 --> 00:54:22.220
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder:
Had it been better,

00:54:22.220 --> 00:54:23.520
maybe the conversation might
have been more interesting.

00:54:23.520 --> 00:54:26.160
But it was just not -- it
was shallow is my point.

00:54:26.160 --> 00:54:28.350
It was like it was -- it
didn't really actually sound

00:54:28.350 --> 00:54:32.280
like a person in that
position talking, first of all.

00:54:32.280 --> 00:54:34.200
And second of all,
the point of making

00:54:34.200 --> 00:54:37.380
that a poem altogether
seemed kind of --

00:54:37.380 --> 00:54:39.300
like what was the
point of doing that?

00:54:39.300 --> 00:54:43.180
Like why just sort of -- that
didn't even seem like a --

00:54:43.180 --> 00:54:45.290
like I won't say appropriate,
because that makes sense, too.

00:54:45.290 --> 00:54:46.590
Ethical, I just mentioned.

00:54:46.590 --> 00:54:49.010
But just useful thing
to do as a poem.

00:54:49.010 --> 00:54:51.400
And so I didn't really get --
I thought they did a bad job

00:54:51.400 --> 00:54:52.700
by picking that poem,

00:54:52.700 --> 00:54:55.390
and I thought they should have
stuck behind their choice.

00:54:55.390 --> 00:54:57.520
I thought they threw
the poem under the bus

00:54:57.520 --> 00:54:58.820
and they shouldn't have done

00:54:58.820 --> 00:55:00.120
that because once
you pick something,

00:55:00.120 --> 00:55:01.420
you should stand behind it.

00:55:01.420 --> 00:55:03.870
It's not right to throw a
young poet under the bus.

00:55:03.870 --> 00:55:05.800
And I'm friends with
both those people,

00:55:05.800 --> 00:55:07.110
but I didn't like what they did.

00:55:07.110 --> 00:55:09.660
And -- but I also
thought the poem was bad.

00:55:09.660 --> 00:55:11.690
So I thought the whole
thing was a mess.

00:55:11.690 --> 00:55:12.990
&gt;&gt; Srikanth Reddy: Sure.

00:55:12.990 --> 00:55:14.290
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane:
I mean, I think --

00:55:14.290 --> 00:55:15.590
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder:
That's what I think.

00:55:15.590 --> 00:55:16.890
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: -- I
think, you know, you know,

00:55:16.890 --> 00:55:18.950
Matthew just very
economically laid out a lot

00:55:18.950 --> 00:55:20.250
of my thought processes.

00:55:20.250 --> 00:55:25.240
And I do think, too -- and,
again, this may be pivoting away

00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:27.330
from the premises
of your question,

00:55:27.330 --> 00:55:31.810
but I do think this was also
something about the temporality

00:55:31.810 --> 00:55:33.770
of reading and what those
kind of Twitter outcry.

00:55:33.770 --> 00:55:37.620
And I think that
there's a sense --

00:55:37.620 --> 00:55:41.060
I think that was an apology
written under enormous pressure.

00:55:41.060 --> 00:55:45.440
And that is the situation
we are in now.

00:55:45.440 --> 00:55:49.210
We're in a situation of
reactivity all the time.

00:55:49.210 --> 00:55:54.120
And so the space to have
a conversation about --

00:55:54.120 --> 00:55:58.730
and these things are
unavoidable and necessary,

00:55:58.730 --> 00:56:01.700
whether you're talking
appropriation, ventriloquism,

00:56:01.700 --> 00:56:04.280
varieties of American
vernacular English,

00:56:04.280 --> 00:56:06.070
who speaks, who gets to speak.

00:56:06.070 --> 00:56:07.680
I was quite taken aback,

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:09.580
and I thought it was
not helpful comment --

00:56:09.580 --> 00:56:12.260
Roxanne Gaye, a write
whom I enormously admire,

00:56:12.260 --> 00:56:13.830
you know [inaudible]
stay in your lane,

00:56:13.830 --> 00:56:15.770
and I'm like, wow, you know?

00:56:15.770 --> 00:56:17.070
So I didn't feel like --

00:56:17.070 --> 00:56:20.300
you know, all of us are having
inner cops activated a lot,

00:56:20.300 --> 00:56:22.880
and that's pretty depressing.

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:24.990
But it's also is
sort of where we are.

00:56:24.990 --> 00:56:28.180
And so I can't help but feel --

00:56:28.180 --> 00:56:31.090
it partly seemed to me like
this glorious horrible symptom

00:56:31.090 --> 00:56:32.960
of a lot of things.

00:56:32.960 --> 00:56:36.750
And that the -- what
does one call it?

00:56:36.750 --> 00:56:39.090
The -- like not even the
24-hour news cycle, but --

00:56:39.090 --> 00:56:40.670
&gt;&gt; Srikanth Reddy: Spin cycle.

00:56:40.670 --> 00:56:43.170
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: --
spin cycle was so intense.

00:56:43.170 --> 00:56:45.970
One could understand why they
did write such an apology,

00:56:45.970 --> 00:56:48.200
but I also thought it was
milquetoasty and weird.

00:56:48.200 --> 00:56:52.840
And I do feel -- I think very
much that editing and curating

00:56:52.840 --> 00:56:56.200
and organizing lecture series
is a form of criticism.

00:56:56.200 --> 00:56:58.750
That's -- and that's why
anthologies are so important,

00:56:58.750 --> 00:57:00.470
and syllabi, and all that.

00:57:00.470 --> 00:57:01.770
So --

00:57:01.770 --> 00:57:03.070
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: Jump in?

00:57:03.070 --> 00:57:04.370
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: Yeah, but I
think that the difference is

00:57:04.370 --> 00:57:07.980
that the apology was not --
I think that as a critic,

00:57:07.980 --> 00:57:09.870
you can write as
strong defense of a poem

00:57:09.870 --> 00:57:11.820
and then you can
change your mind, right?

00:57:11.820 --> 00:57:13.860
As an editor, you
publish a poem --

00:57:13.860 --> 00:57:15.160
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: Right.

00:57:15.160 --> 00:57:17.800
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: -- and then
to kind of retract it is to --

00:57:17.800 --> 00:57:21.180
I think it goes against the
role one takes on as an editor

00:57:21.180 --> 00:57:23.930
and pushing forward work
that you believe in.

00:57:23.930 --> 00:57:25.410
So I understood why
they had to do it.

00:57:25.410 --> 00:57:26.850
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: Can I
just say one quick thing,

00:57:26.850 --> 00:57:29.110
which is that it's depressing
that the amount of time

00:57:29.110 --> 00:57:32.590
and energy that was devoted to
the discussion of this, at best,

00:57:32.590 --> 00:57:37.290
mediocre poem, was compared
to all the other work

00:57:37.290 --> 00:57:39.220
that has been published
recently.

00:57:39.220 --> 00:57:40.550
It was absurd.

00:57:40.550 --> 00:57:42.760
And it was depressing as a poet
to watch this because it --

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:45.170
just people just cannot
stop talking about this

00:57:45.170 --> 00:57:47.440
because they love to
watch poets misbehave.

00:57:47.440 --> 00:57:48.830
And they -- so people
do anything

00:57:48.830 --> 00:57:50.860
but then actually talk
about what you saw.

00:57:50.860 --> 00:57:53.460
I'm not saying it wasn't an
interesting topic of discussion,

00:57:53.460 --> 00:57:55.110
but it's like even that
it became, you know,

00:57:55.110 --> 00:57:58.160
this conversation is a little
-- was a little like grim to me,

00:57:58.160 --> 00:58:00.500
I felt like, but it
preferred [inaudible].

00:58:00.500 --> 00:58:02.340
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: I don't think
that makes it easy for someone

00:58:02.340 --> 00:58:03.640
to ask another question.

00:58:03.640 --> 00:58:05.440
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder:
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:58:05.440 --> 00:58:08.040
[ Multiple Speakers
and Laughter ]

00:58:08.040 --> 00:58:09.340
&gt;&gt; No.

00:58:09.340 --> 00:58:10.640
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: Thank you.

00:58:10.640 --> 00:58:11.940
Thank you.

00:58:11.940 --> 00:58:13.240
&gt;&gt; Hi.

00:58:13.240 --> 00:58:14.540
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: Hi.

00:58:14.540 --> 00:58:16.340
&gt;&gt; I enjoyed the discussion,
so thank you for that.

00:58:16.340 --> 00:58:20.040
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:58:20.040 --> 00:58:21.340
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane:
Not Facebook per se,

00:58:21.340 --> 00:58:22.640
although maybe [inaudible].

00:58:22.640 --> 00:58:24.250
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder:
Like and dislike.

00:58:24.250 --> 00:58:27.430
&gt;&gt; It was [inaudible] Facebook
as far as the type of discussion

00:58:27.430 --> 00:58:30.990
that creates in some instances.

00:58:30.990 --> 00:58:33.090
By the way, if and
when you think

00:58:33.090 --> 00:58:35.330
of something [inaudible] a
long time ago [inaudible].

00:58:35.330 --> 00:58:40.230
It's a moment of communication
of the social media

00:58:40.230 --> 00:58:42.530
as a whole kind of
has this unique place

00:58:42.530 --> 00:58:46.310
in that it's really been
free of [inaudible] sort

00:58:46.310 --> 00:58:51.330
of critical treatment because
been on television books.

00:58:51.330 --> 00:58:52.670
Even other magazines

00:58:52.670 --> 00:58:56.980
and newspapers have always
had this sort of sidecar

00:58:56.980 --> 00:59:00.940
with them talking about how
they function and their uses,

00:59:00.940 --> 00:59:05.710
where as social media, which
is -- were seen as, you know,

00:59:05.710 --> 00:59:07.080
downstream lighthouses.

00:59:07.080 --> 00:59:12.950
Maybe the most powerful
form of communication,

00:59:12.950 --> 00:59:16.310
at least in the last
hundred years come out.

00:59:16.310 --> 00:59:20.880
And within that realm
now we see the emergence

00:59:20.880 --> 00:59:22.730
of what's called [inaudible].

00:59:22.730 --> 00:59:25.160
And I guess my question
is twofold,

00:59:25.160 --> 00:59:34.100
which is do you see social
media as a form of communication

00:59:34.100 --> 00:59:37.460
that does exist outside
of the reach of criticism?

00:59:37.460 --> 00:59:44.710
And if so, how do
you handle something

00:59:44.710 --> 00:59:47.370
like the incredible
popularity [inaudible].

00:59:47.370 --> 00:59:48.670
We just had [inaudible].

00:59:48.670 --> 00:59:55.500
She sold out two nights of,
I think, the Lincoln Theater,

00:59:55.500 --> 01:00:00.030
and those are people that
are getting more raves

01:00:00.030 --> 01:00:01.330
on an individual [inaudible].

01:00:01.330 --> 01:00:02.630
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: Yeah.

01:00:02.630 --> 01:00:03.930
&gt;&gt; You know on a daily basis.

01:00:03.930 --> 01:00:06.750
So just what are your
thoughts on that one?

01:00:08.310 --> 01:00:11.000
And, yeah, [inaudible].

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:12.910
Thank you.

01:00:12.910 --> 01:00:14.770
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: I
mean, I'm agnostic.

01:00:14.770 --> 01:00:16.070
I'm sort of come all ye.

01:00:16.070 --> 01:00:18.010
And I sort of feel like --

01:00:18.010 --> 01:00:20.600
I tend to think of not
poetry, but poetries.

01:00:20.600 --> 01:00:23.600
And I think that there
are lots of different ways

01:00:23.600 --> 01:00:29.200
that people encounter poems
people write for platforms,

01:00:29.200 --> 01:00:31.700
people write for
communities, people write

01:00:31.700 --> 01:00:33.690
out of traditions
and genealogies.

01:00:33.690 --> 01:00:37.020
Some of them might
be fellow poets.

01:00:37.020 --> 01:00:39.570
Some of them might be
thinking with Homer.

01:00:39.570 --> 01:00:43.770
Some of them might be
thinking with James Skylar.

01:00:43.770 --> 01:00:46.300
Some of them might
be the interface

01:00:46.300 --> 01:00:47.820
of poetry and pop music.

01:00:47.820 --> 01:00:49.210
Some of the -- and
I sort of feel

01:00:49.210 --> 01:00:52.530
like I could have a sociological
response to that which is,

01:00:52.530 --> 01:00:58.610
you know, mass culture creates
new niches for communication.

01:00:58.610 --> 01:01:04.940
Okay. So I just sort of
feel like more power to you.

01:01:04.940 --> 01:01:08.830
And I also feel, you
know, the question --

01:01:08.830 --> 01:01:10.960
it's a very interesting
question, too, about,

01:01:10.960 --> 01:01:14.500
as you said, like sidecars
going with older media forms

01:01:14.500 --> 01:01:17.230
and that there's just
probably starting

01:01:17.230 --> 01:01:20.260
to be a more robust kind of
sociological conversation

01:01:20.260 --> 01:01:21.750
or [inaudible] aesthetic
conversation

01:01:21.750 --> 01:01:23.750
about what is the
logic of Twitter?

01:01:23.750 --> 01:01:25.600
Are people like tweeting
entire novels?

01:01:25.600 --> 01:01:27.550
Or the question of
restricted form.

01:01:27.550 --> 01:01:31.310
Does the 140 character
tweet actually lend itself

01:01:31.310 --> 01:01:33.770
to a possible striking form?

01:01:33.770 --> 01:01:36.950
So I'm kind of -- I kind of --

01:01:36.950 --> 01:01:39.950
this is a thing that I don't get
my knickers in a twist about.

01:01:39.950 --> 01:01:44.390
And partly -- this is a thing
where I find consolation in --

01:01:44.390 --> 01:01:48.750
or, if not consolation, maybe
provisional balance in thinking

01:01:48.750 --> 01:01:54.770
about broadside culture or
tradition, and Bali culture,

01:01:54.770 --> 01:01:59.530
and population poets of the 19th
century who somebody like, say,

01:01:59.530 --> 01:02:02.090
Emerson or Hawthorne, would have
to spend like, uhh, you know,

01:02:02.090 --> 01:02:03.390
put them in the trash bin.

01:02:03.390 --> 01:02:07.400
But there are many ways
to live in and with verse.

01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:10.290
And not all poetry is verse,
not all verse is poetry.

01:02:10.290 --> 01:02:12.350
So I'm kind of pivoting
away from your question.

01:02:12.350 --> 01:02:16.800
But I just -- I feel like
there's a kind of Venn diagram

01:02:16.800 --> 01:02:21.230
of intersection and there's like
a slim intersection between some

01:02:21.230 --> 01:02:22.530
of these things and
some other matters.

01:02:22.530 --> 01:02:27.780
I also encounter some very good
critical discussions sometimes

01:02:27.780 --> 01:02:30.910
on Facebook even though I do
feel it like, it rots my brain.

01:02:30.910 --> 01:02:32.310
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: Yeah,
that was my question.

01:02:32.310 --> 01:02:36.430
Is social media offering a new
kind of venue for criticism,

01:02:36.430 --> 01:02:37.730
new ways to think
about criticism?

01:02:37.730 --> 01:02:41.430
Or does it just feel like it
likes/dislikes predominating?

01:02:43.040 --> 01:02:44.470
&gt;&gt; Srikanth Reddy: I'm not
on social media [laughter],

01:02:44.470 --> 01:02:47.130
so I'm not very qualified
to answer.

01:02:47.130 --> 01:02:50.770
But maybe that qualifies me
to imagine its possibilities

01:02:50.770 --> 01:02:55.370
in a more utopian or dystopian
kind of way as a non-user.

01:02:55.370 --> 01:03:00.070
And, you know, I can imagine
that one problem of -- no.

01:03:00.070 --> 01:03:02.810
You can imagine like Walt
Whitman saying Facebook is the

01:03:02.810 --> 01:03:05.180
greatest poem on end, you know,

01:03:05.180 --> 01:03:08.400
that there's all these
immense possibilities,

01:03:08.400 --> 01:03:09.700
right, in the [inaudible].

01:03:09.700 --> 01:03:15.340
You know, I can imagine that
the 140-character tweet is

01:03:15.340 --> 01:03:21.740
as compelling formally as
the haiku form or, you know,

01:03:21.740 --> 01:03:24.750
or has potentialities within
it that are as compelling

01:03:24.750 --> 01:03:26.830
as any other formal constraint.

01:03:26.830 --> 01:03:32.240
But I think that the thing
that I would wonder about, and,

01:03:32.240 --> 01:03:34.190
again, I'm not qualified
to comment on it

01:03:34.190 --> 01:03:36.290
because I just have too much
of an addictive personality

01:03:36.290 --> 01:03:38.220
to ever go on social media,

01:03:38.220 --> 01:03:43.830
is that I think popularity
can leave a metric of value.

01:03:43.830 --> 01:03:45.130
And it seems that --

01:03:45.130 --> 01:03:46.430
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder:
What [laughter]?

01:03:46.430 --> 01:03:51.500
&gt;&gt; Srikanth Reddy: But like --
but are there like actual kinds

01:03:51.500 --> 01:03:57.320
of communities and
opportunities or potentialities

01:03:57.320 --> 01:04:03.880
within social media for more
kind of sophisticated ways

01:04:03.880 --> 01:04:08.500
of thinking about what
literary value might be

01:04:08.500 --> 01:04:10.900
within that formal practice.

01:04:10.900 --> 01:04:12.200
I don't know.

01:04:12.200 --> 01:04:13.500
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: Yeah.

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:14.800
First of all, tweets
are now 280 [laughter].

01:04:14.800 --> 01:04:16.100
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: Yeah, right.

01:04:16.100 --> 01:04:17.640
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: That's
talking about odd thing about,

01:04:17.640 --> 01:04:20.150
and I'm sure other people in
this room have noticed this,

01:04:20.150 --> 01:04:24.760
but is that -- so tweets,
when they were 140 characters,

01:04:24.760 --> 01:04:27.880
that's also the same
number of words, syllable --

01:04:27.880 --> 01:04:30.530
that would be the exact word
in syllabic kind of a sonnet --

01:04:30.530 --> 01:04:31.830
&gt;&gt; Srikanth Reddy: Uh-huh.

01:04:31.830 --> 01:04:33.130
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: -- right?

01:04:33.130 --> 01:04:35.700
So the 10 iambic pentameter
sonnet would be 10 beats,

01:04:35.700 --> 01:04:37.000
14 [inaudible] and [inaudible],

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:39.850
that seems like a totally
irrelevant coincidence,

01:04:39.850 --> 01:04:43.010
but I just thought
I'd point it out.

01:04:43.010 --> 01:04:45.310
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: One
more question right here.

01:04:46.890 --> 01:04:51.390
&gt;&gt; I just found that in
reading criticism by poets,

01:04:51.390 --> 01:04:58.070
that one of the exciting
things [inaudible] was not the

01:04:58.070 --> 01:05:01.370
descriptive value of
the role that they play,

01:05:01.370 --> 01:05:03.500
but the prospective role.

01:05:03.500 --> 01:05:05.510
I think [inaudible]
one by [inaudible]

01:05:05.510 --> 01:05:10.580
but also [inaudible] Stevens
writing very [inaudible] the

01:05:10.580 --> 01:05:13.140
[inaudible] about
like the poet of --

01:05:13.140 --> 01:05:15.280
sorry, the poem of
Al [inaudible].

01:05:15.280 --> 01:05:18.700
And then he starts talking
about well, what is the poem

01:05:18.700 --> 01:05:20.170
of [inaudible], for instance.

01:05:20.170 --> 01:05:25.520
And as someone who likes also to
write poetry, I find that type

01:05:25.520 --> 01:05:27.860
of praise that I
read a criticism

01:05:27.860 --> 01:05:31.830
by poets really inspiring
and useful.

01:05:31.830 --> 01:05:34.490
And I wonder if you
find it the same way.

01:05:34.490 --> 01:05:38.070
Are you inspired by
criticism of that sort?

01:05:38.070 --> 01:05:43.930
And do you see a role for this
sort of perspective criticism

01:05:43.930 --> 01:05:46.180
when a poet turns to prose

01:05:46.180 --> 01:05:48.950
to describe the thing
they can't quite achieve

01:05:48.950 --> 01:05:51.250
in their own heart [inaudible]?

01:05:54.040 --> 01:05:56.130
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane: You question
reminds me of Matthew's,

01:05:56.130 --> 01:05:59.690
you know, very beautiful opening
up of Shelly's defensive poetry

01:05:59.690 --> 01:06:03.300
which ends with this whole
question of poetry and futurity.

01:06:03.300 --> 01:06:05.630
And that whole thing
about, what is it?

01:06:05.630 --> 01:06:07.730
Poet to the higher offense
of an unapprehended --

01:06:07.730 --> 01:06:09.030
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: Mm-hmm.

01:06:09.030 --> 01:06:10.330
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane:
-- inspiration.

01:06:10.330 --> 01:06:11.630
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder:
Inspiration.

01:06:11.630 --> 01:06:12.930
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane:
And it's all about --

01:06:12.930 --> 01:06:14.230
it's like what is
not yet apprehended?

01:06:14.230 --> 01:06:15.530
What is not yet legislated?

01:06:15.530 --> 01:06:16.830
What might yet happen?

01:06:16.830 --> 01:06:20.130
And that's also a key
in Emerson, you know?

01:06:20.130 --> 01:06:23.270
It's like the Poem of America
does not yet, you know?

01:06:23.270 --> 01:06:24.700
And it's a call for.

01:06:24.700 --> 01:06:28.230
And so people talk
about a kind of --

01:06:28.230 --> 01:06:31.070
this is why a manifesto
[inaudible] very dogmatic

01:06:31.070 --> 01:06:34.000
and they can feel like you're
being amputated, you know?

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:38.180
But it is so wonderful when
one encounters something

01:06:38.180 --> 01:06:40.350
that feels enabling
or inspiring.

01:06:40.350 --> 01:06:43.500
And I definitely feel that,

01:06:43.500 --> 01:06:45.740
in a certain key,
Shelley is like that.

01:06:45.740 --> 01:06:50.220
Or if you read some of
Anne Carson's essays,

01:06:50.220 --> 01:06:53.220
they open up doors or
open up some possibilities

01:06:53.220 --> 01:06:55.330
that one might not
have thought of.

01:06:55.330 --> 01:06:59.560
And that might be the most
-- you have that sense that,

01:06:59.560 --> 01:07:02.690
you know, you would expand
your own either thinking

01:07:02.690 --> 01:07:04.240
or writing or reading practice.

01:07:04.240 --> 01:07:09.440
I mean that seems to me the real
gift of these kinds of essays,

01:07:09.440 --> 01:07:13.010
books, et cetera, when they
actually can resonate that way.

01:07:14.070 --> 01:07:15.370
&gt;&gt; Srikanth Reddy: Yeah.

01:07:15.370 --> 01:07:17.390
I think that's a great question
to end on in a lot of ways.

01:07:17.390 --> 01:07:19.400
I think that kind of --

01:07:19.400 --> 01:07:27.140
and prospective would be in some
ways like my ideal for what kind

01:07:27.140 --> 01:07:33.080
of criticism would do, right,
rather then proscriptive.

01:07:33.080 --> 01:07:36.630
And I don't know that -- I mean,

01:07:36.630 --> 01:07:39.970
I think we can have
more of that.

01:07:39.970 --> 01:07:44.560
But that would require also --
that requires thinking outside

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:49.470
of the 250-word review or,
you know, the different kinds

01:07:49.470 --> 01:07:51.860
of media outlets for criticism.

01:07:51.860 --> 01:07:56.250
And this is why things
like the lecture are a form

01:07:56.250 --> 01:07:59.540
for thinking possibilities
for poetry.

01:07:59.540 --> 01:08:03.420
And I think that, you know,
that's what the poet critic

01:08:03.420 --> 01:08:05.490
in some ways, you know,
would [inaudible].

01:08:05.490 --> 01:08:07.210
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: I mean,

01:08:07.210 --> 01:08:09.110
when poets write
criticism they use words

01:08:09.110 --> 01:08:14.020
like higher fats [laughter]
or luxury or nobility --

01:08:14.020 --> 01:08:15.520
&gt;&gt; Maureen McLane:
Negative capability.

01:08:15.520 --> 01:08:17.900
&gt;&gt; Matthew Zapruder: -- or
duende, negative capability

01:08:17.900 --> 01:08:19.560
which was in a letter

01:08:19.560 --> 01:08:21.770
that [inaudible]
wrote to his brothers.

01:08:21.770 --> 01:08:25.630
That's -- and they write those
words because they are poets

01:08:25.630 --> 01:08:29.370
and they can't help but
ultimately be preoccupied

01:08:29.370 --> 01:08:31.960
with the texture and
possibilities of language

01:08:31.960 --> 01:08:33.970
and probably words
that they're --

01:08:33.970 --> 01:08:35.660
that they have an
instinct apply,

01:08:35.660 --> 01:08:37.170
but they're not totally sure.

01:08:37.170 --> 01:08:41.080
And a lot of the criticism
about poets is kind of a --

01:08:41.080 --> 01:08:44.560
often is a sort of exploration
of the use or association

01:08:44.560 --> 01:08:47.190
of a certain word
with importance.

01:08:47.190 --> 01:08:52.170
And a kind of instinctive
choice that's then justified

01:08:52.170 --> 01:08:54.280
in the course of the
essay or the lecture.

01:08:54.280 --> 01:08:57.250
And that's just not
how academics

01:08:57.250 --> 01:08:59.760
and generally write criticism.

01:08:59.760 --> 01:09:01.800
I mean, you know, it's --

01:09:01.800 --> 01:09:04.280
they have a different way
of approaching the work.

01:09:04.280 --> 01:09:06.790
It's just -- and so
that's probably why I

01:09:06.790 --> 01:09:09.330
like poetry written, but
criticism [inaudible] better

01:09:09.330 --> 01:09:13.510
because it operates in a kind
of way that poems operate, too.

01:09:13.510 --> 01:09:17.000
It comes out of the love of, not
just the poetry like some kind

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:21.380
of weird abstract thing, but out
of a love of language and words.

01:09:21.380 --> 01:09:23.990
And those are the most
memorable moments to me.

01:09:23.990 --> 01:09:25.680
And I think they've had
a profound influence

01:09:25.680 --> 01:09:27.860
on our thinking about
poetry, actually.

01:09:27.860 --> 01:09:31.990
I mean this -- you brought up
Coleridge, but Wordsworth's,

01:09:31.990 --> 01:09:34.870
you know, "Introduction
to the Lyrical Ballads"

01:09:34.870 --> 01:09:39.940
in 1799 is the single most
important poetic statement

01:09:39.940 --> 01:09:42.660
that was made for a long time.

01:09:42.660 --> 01:09:45.730
It's deeply influenced even
today our ideas about --

01:09:45.730 --> 01:09:49.310
and if you read that, you see
general ideas about poetry

01:09:49.310 --> 01:09:50.610
and what people think.

01:09:50.610 --> 01:09:51.960
And it's -- these
are, these are --

01:09:51.960 --> 01:09:55.140
this is meaningful work
in terms of the practice

01:09:55.140 --> 01:09:57.730
and understanding
of poetry, so, yeah.

01:09:57.730 --> 01:09:59.240
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper: On that
